<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-133-066 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 825 998</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 10 1991 v10 n12 p84(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GSA urges moving more services to FTS. (US General ServicesAdministration mandates use of Federal Telecommunications System2000)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Masud, S.A.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Services AdministrationFederal Telecommunications System 2000 (Computer network)Telecommunications ServicesGovernment AgencyInformation resources managementGovernment Regulation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>To re-enforce mandatory use of the FTS 2000 network, the General ServicesAdministration has told agencies to terminate some independently purchasedtelecommunications services and acquired them through the new FTS network.andM;&quot;There are some significant chunks of business out there that we can glueonto the network,&quot; said Michael Corrigan, assistant commissioner fortelecommunications services in GSA's IRM Service.andM;GSA has sent letters to senior IRM officials urging the swithc to FTS 2000,Corrigan said last month at a Government Computer News Forum luncheon inWahsington.andM;The letters clarify GSA's Bulletin 60, which provides guidance on mandatoryuse, Corrigan said.andP;  GSA tried to spell out the type of services agenciesshould acquire outside the FTS contracts, he said.andM;Non-FTS 2000 services can continue to use include calling card privileges,dedicated transmission circuits with tarified services, and long-distanceservices supplied to small federal locations by primary interexchangecarriers.andM;Agencies also must require that systems integrators providingtelecommunications as part of larger projects use FTS 2000 for long-haulservices.andM;Corrigan said because this is a &quot;complex process&quot; requiring renegotiation ofexisting contracts, GSA, will allow agencies extensive time to make changes.andM;GSA's other immediate FTS 2000 priorities include providing users with theautomatic number identification (ANI) capability and converting from theseven-digit and converting from the seven-digit FTS 2000 numbering system tothe standard 10-digit dialing system.andM;Corrigan said GSA has made progress on both issues.andP;  With ANI capability, FTS2000 users can obtain the detailed billing information they have beenseeking.andM;Although GSA completed conversion of voice services from the old FTS to FTS2000 last year, the new network will continue to grow as agencies moveadditional services, Corrigan predicted.andM;The Social Security Administration is scheduled to transfer its 800 serviceto the new network, and the Agriculture Department will move its nationwidepacket-switching network, Depnet, to ATandamp;T Co.'s portion of FTS 2000 byOctober, Corrigan said.andM;SSA now has a contract with MCI Communiations Corp. for its 800 service.andP;  USSprint Communications Co., under an earlier Communications Co., under anearlier non-FTS 2000 pact, provides Depnet services to Agriculture.andM;Corrigan said GSA also wants FTS 2000 to provide interperableelectronic-mail, packet-switching and video teleconferencing services.andO;</TEXT></DOC>